### Customer situation

<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">Contoso, Ltd. (Contoso) is a new company in an old business. The company was founded in Auckland, New Zealand, in 2011, by senior life insurance executives. The ambitious new company provides a full range of long-term insurance services to help underinsured people.The company was founded in Auckland, New Zealand, in 2011, by senior life insurance executives. The ambitious new company provides a full range of long-term insurance services to help underinsured people.</span>

<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">Almost from the start, the company grew far faster than anticipated. The company has multiple offices and many of the staff work from home. The company relied on custom built software and each department had their own technology team. After several re-organizations a new CIO has been brought in to assist with getting the entire IT staff working as one single team. One of the headaches the CIO wants to address is creating collaboration spaces for people with expertise in similar technologies. Rather than creating guessing at what collaboration spaces are need and their priority the CTO has decided to use automation to create the spaces. So if a particular team is strong in SharePoint development they should easily be able to find and share ideas with each other. Additionally, this will enable other IT staff to seek out information from expert teams quickly. Thus users with similar skillsets can 'Keep in Touch' with each other to share ideas, issues, share updates, & security information about their particular skillsets. The goal of the application is to the IT staff engaged with technologies they are proficient in and additionally offer the opprtunity to peek into other skills sets they might have interests in.</span>

<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">To overcome this challenge the CTO has decided that all IT staff will utilize their Outlook profiles to list their strongest skill sets.</span>
<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">![editprofile.png](data:image/png;base64,)</span>
Based on the individuals in IT adding skills a backend process will utilize Teams to automatically create Channels based on skills that have more than two users.
![TeamsAndChannels.png](data:image/png;base64,)

<br>
### Customer Needs

1. Contoso wants to extend the existing Icebreaker application and re-use as much as possible.
2. The initial release will not have any approval workflows for Channel creation.

### Customer Objections

1. The CTO doesn't want any .Net code written to make the app more supportable and extendable by multiple IT groups.
2. There should not be any additional long running compute time resources added (Database, web server, etc)

## Step 3a: Present the solution

<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">**Outcome**</span>

<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">Present a solution to the target customer audience in a 15-minute chalk-talk format.</span>
<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">Before beginning ensure that at least two users have been setup in Azure Active Directory and the users have been given the Office 365 E3 Developer access.</span>
<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">![licenses.png](data:image/png;base64,)</span>
<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">Then login as each user to [https://office.com](https://office.com)and visit their Outlook profile and click the link in the middle of the page to "Add skills and expertise." Add at least one matching skill for each of the users in their respective profiles. To simplify use the same case in both profiles (HTML = HTML).</span>
<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">![profile.png](data:image/png;base64,)</span>
<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">Starting with the Cosmos DB that was provisioned with the IceBreaker app. Start by adding a new container with userPrincipalName as the Partition key</span>

1. ActiveUsers

<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">![addcontainer.png](data:image/png;base64,)</span>

In the Azure portal visit Azure Active Directory. Because it is necessary to read information from the Graph API we need to add permissions.

* Click on App Registrations and select the Application registered when creating the IceBreaker app. Then click on API Permissions in the left-hand navigations.
* Click on the Add a permission button.
* Click on the Microsoft Graph button
* Click on Application permissions
* Scroll down till the Users permission section is visible and check User.Read.All
* Finally click Add permissions

![user-profile-permission.png](data:image/png;base64,)

<span class="colour" style="color:rgb(36, 41, 46)">Next open Graph Explorer and sign in with your Azure credentials to validate the permissions that were just setup. This will involve running two simple queries. The first just gets a simple list of all the users setup in Azure Active Directory</span>
[https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/users/](https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/users/)
![user-profile.png](data:image/png;base64,)
Choose on of the users you setup with a profile and copy the id value. Open a new tab to Graph Explorer and run the following query to validate you can get the users profile information.
[https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/users/{id}?$select=userPrincipalName,displayName,skills,responsibilities](https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/users/%7Bb4f76103-ed67-4e8c-92bb-05c6f60ec42e%7D?$select=userPrincipalName,displayName,skills,responsibilities)
